For zen3_0512, there are 128 cpu cores and 256 logical cores
For zen3_1024, there are 128 cpu cores and 256 logical cores
However, the default ntasks-per-node of slurm on VSC5 is 128, which means you are only allowed 
to use 128 logical cores on each node, but you have to be aware that, when a job is running on these 128 logical cores
you are actually taking up all the 256 logical cores and all the 500 GB memory space.


Note that the number you use in mpirun refers to number of logical cores
for example
mpirun -np 128 vasp_std 
this command means you are using 128 logical cores


For VSC5, even though you specify ntasks-per-node = 16 in bash script, you are still using the memory of the entire node
say, you request one zen3_0512 node, which provides the user 500 GB memory 
and 128 logical cores(only 128 logical cores are allowed to use at most on each node, as I mentioned above)
since you specify ntasks-per-node = 16, that means you are 
requesting 16 logical cores from each node and 500 GB memory from each node
but, let me say this again, when a job is running on these 16 logical cores on each node, you are 
actually taking up all the 256 logical cores (yes, you have 240 logical cores keeping idle) and 500 GB memory on each node



If you want to find the maximal logical cores allowed to request for QOS=p70623_1028, execute command below

sacctmgr show qos p70623_1028 format=Name,GrpTRES,MaxTRESPerJob,MaxWall,GrpJobs,Preempt

you will see output like this:
      Name       GrpTRES       MaxTRES     MaxWall GrpJobs    Preempt 
---------- ------------- ------------- ----------- ------- ---------- 
p70623_10+      cpu=1280               10-00:00:00                    

GrpTRES means there are 1280 logical cores (5 nodes) at most allowed to be requested(including those already occupied) for 
this QOS for all users in current group.




You could also list all the jobs running under this QOS=p70623_1028 to get more information:
squeue -q p70623_1028 -t RUNNING -o "%.18i %.9u %.6C %.5D %R"

You could also list all the jobs pending under this QOS=p70623_1028 to get more information:
squeue -q p70623_1028 -t PENDING -o "%.18i %.9u %.6C %.5D %R"

